CH15

Then James the Just was stoned and struck on the head with a fuller’s club until he gave up his spirit, praying for those who killed him, saying, “YHWH, forgive them, for they know not what they do.” And he was gathered to the righteous, having finished his testimony in Jerusalem.
The brothers buried him with great honor near the temple, and the church was greatly sorrowed, yet they rejoiced that he had received the crown of martyrdom.
James the brother of the Lord stood firm before the high priest and the council, declaring that Yeshua the Anointed is the Son of the living God and the door of salvation. Many believed because of his words.
Thus James completed his course with joy, having taught the perfect law of liberty and shown mercy to the poor. He was called “the Just” by all the people for his righteousness.
The Lord received James into glory, for he had been a pillar of the church and a witness to the resurrection. His knees became like those of a camel from much prayer.
After the ascension of the Lord, James the brother of the Lord received the oversight of the church in Jerusalem and led the apostles and elders with wisdom.

